SynthesisResultsItem:
The reviewed literature reveals a consensus on the critical role of trustworthiness in agentic AI software frameworks, particularly in high-risk deployments. Qi et al. (2026) provide a comprehensive survey emphasizing that agentic systems, unlike static language models, introduce amplified risks due to their multi-step trajectories and tool-mediated interactions. Key design patterns for fault-tolerance and safety include runtime safeguards (e.g., anomaly monitors, permission gates, and sandboxing), workflow-aligned mitigation strategies (e.g., constrained optimization and red teaming), and process-aware evaluation metrics (e.g., constraint violation rates and trace completeness). The Perceive→Plan→Act→Reflect→Learn loop is identified as a consistent architectural interface for mapping threats and defenses, with assurance hooks (e.g., validation, verification, and diagnostics) integrated at each stage. Farooq (2026) complements this by proposing structured benchmarks and regulatory frameworks to standardize transparency and accountability, while Terragni et al. (2025) highlight the future trajectory of AI-driven software engineering, underscoring the need for adaptive fault-tolerance mechanisms in evolving agent ecosystems.

